Some notes on final work done:

I'm trying to frame my section of the powerpoint in terms of different workflow steps taken to get from an EOS / opacities to an emergent spectrum, even if the EOS isn't entirely accurate.

1. interpolation of opacities onto temperature and pressure grid

this includes the interpolation chunks of the code, and dealing with the results of EOS and opacity calculations to get onto grids of temperature and pressure. I made the below figure to visualise what we were dealing with for density and pressure trends in opacity.

![!\[\[Pasted image 20251007094931.png\]\]](<Pasted image 20251007094931.png>)

2. Internal spectrum

Focusing on the idea of stacking the spectra of each layer, weighted by optical depth, to get a final spectrum. The internal spectrum is a result of the weighting of various optical depths, so the fact that the brighter spectra are not being counted is a product of the fact that the opacities / optical depth grid are problematic. A better opacity grid would result in a very different picture of internal spectrum.

**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

3. Adding the irradiated spectrum

The distance between star and exoplanet makes large difference on the impact of the irradiated spectrum, as does the $\kappa_J/\kappa_B$ ratio. I have previously made notes on the opacities ratio but the main point here is that a high ratio goes hand in hand with strong irradiation, further enhancing the curve. However this doesn't take into account the effect of atmospheric chemistry.

![!\[\[Pasted image 20251007102030.png\]\]](<Pasted image 20251007102030.png>)

4. Absorption lines (next steps)

Getting the line strengths of atmospheric molecules isn't the issue, its incorporating this into the opacities and EOS of the model.  I have been able to make steps towards this in terms of calculating number density and working towards getting it as a column density to get a transmission function. The simplest implementation would be getting the transmission curve set between 0 to 1 and then multiplying the spectra by this.
